hen Toulmin, Karl Popper, Edward O. Wilson, Hilary Putnam, Philip Kitcher, Elliott Sober, and Peter Singer. Readers will encounter some of the staunchest critics of the evolutionary approach, such as Alvin Plantinga, as well as revealing excerpts from works like Jack London's The Call of the Wild. Ruse's comprehensive general introduction and insightful section introductions put these writings in context and explain how they relate to such fields as epistemology, philosophy of mind, philosophy of language, and ethics.An invaluable anthology and sourcebook, Philosophy after Darwin traces philosophy's complicated relationship with Darwin's dangerous idea, and shows how this relationship reflects a broad movement toward a secular, more naturalistic understanding of the human experience.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aEthics. 0aEvolutionary psychology. 0aKnowledge, Theory of. 0aPhilosophy. 7aPHILOSOPHY / General.2bisacsh1 aArnhart, Larry, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBernhardi, Friedrich Von, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBoyd, Craig A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCarnegie, Andrew, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDarwin, Charles, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDe Sousa, Ronald, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDennett, Daniel C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDewey, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEdmonds, Bruce, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aErnst, Zach, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFales, Evan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/